To allow solving anyway, change Files --> Options --> Geometry --> 2D Axisymmetric Check from Error to Warning. Part Transform can also be used to move the geometry to the positive side.

Only one master node is detected on the current condensed part. This is likely to result in a solver error. Please ensure that the condensed part interface has proper master node selection to avoid rigid body motion of the superelement region.

The total number of master nodes across all condensed parts are detected to be high. It is recommended that you define your condensed part interfaces such that the total number of masternodes are less than 10% of the nodes in the entire model or 3000 (whichever is lesser) to avoid slow solver performance.
The interface selection does not share topology with the condensed part geometry

The total number of master degrees of freedom is reduced by the solver. This is probably due to internal constraint equations created by the solver interfering with master degrees of freedom specified in your model. Please check your model carefully for over constraints.
Some of the master nodes is suppressed by specified constraints. Please check your model and review results carefully.
The expansion pass does not show contribution of reactions from the nodes on the condensed parts as the reaction results are not stored for those nodes. Please review your results carefully.
Possible interface connection(s) object added / unsuppressed associated with this solved condensed part. Use 'Detect Condensed Part Interface' option to include these connection(s) as interface(s).
The Condensed Part defined in the model has remote type interface whose behavior is defined as Rigid. This may lead to over constraint and removal of master degrees of freedom.

For combination of symmetry constraint and cyclic repetition constraint, the symmetry plane must be perpendicular to the cyclic repetition rotation axis.
For several symmetry constraints, the symmetry plane must be perpendicular to each other.
For combination of extrusion constraint and symmetry constraint, the extrusion direction must be in the symmetry plane.
For combination of extrusion constraint and cyclic repetition constraint, the rotation axis must be the same as the extrusion direction.
For combination of pull out direction and symmetry constraint, the pull out direction must be in the symmetry plane.
For several pull out direction constraints, the pull out directions must be perpendicular to each other.
For combination of AM overhang constraint and symmetry constraint, the build direction of the AM overhang constraint must be in the symmetry plane.
For combination of pull out direction and cyclic repetition constraint, the rotation axis must be the same as the pull out direction.

For combination of AM overhang constraint and cyclic repetition constraint, the build direction of the AM overhang constraint must be parallel to the axis selection of the cyclic repetition constraint.
For combination of AM overhang constraint and member size constraint, the maximum member size must be unspecified.
For combination of uniform constraint and symmetry constraint, the symmetry plane and the uniform plane must be identical.
For combination of uniform constraint and pattern constraint, the pattern direction must be perpendicular to the uniform plane.
For combination of pattern constraint and pull out direction constraint, the pattern direction must be perpendicular to the pull out direction.
For combination of pattern constraint and extrusion constraint, the pattern direction must be perpendicular to the extrusion direction.
For combination of pattern constraint and cyclic repetition constraint, the pattern direction must be the same as the cyclic repetition rotation axis.
For combination of pattern constraint and symmetry constraint, the pattern direction must be in the symmetry plane.
For combination of pattern constraint and AM overhang constraint, the pattern direction must be perpendicular to the build direction of the AM overhang constraint.
For combination of pattern constraint and pattern constraint, the pattern axis must be perpendicular to each other.

For geometric objective (Mass or Volume), it is recommended to use Criterion of the upstream Measure folder (inserted from Model object).
Mixable Density Optimization supports only Mass, Volume, Compliance, Criterion and Global Stress Response Constraints.

Shape Optimization does not support Temperature and Local von-Mises Stress Constraints, AM Overhang, Pull Out Direction, Housing, Complexity Index Manufacturing Constraints nor Uniform and Pattern Repetition Design Constraints.

Only Mass, Volume, Displacement, Center Of Gravity, Moment Of Inertia, Natural Frequency, Compliance and Global Stress Response Constraints as well as Cyclic Repetition, Symmetry and Pattern Repetition Design Constraints are supported for Lattice Optimization.

Materials Optimization solver only support Mass, Volume, Displacement, UDC, Frequency, Reaction Force, Reaction Moment and Compliance constraints or objective as well as Cyclic Repetition, Symmetry and Pattern Repetition Design Constraints.

This will degrade solver performances and the reaction probe results in the current analysis scoped to a Fixed Support or Displacement boundary conditions may not be available. To improve solver performances or calculate those reactions, please set the "Store Modal Results" property in the linked modal analysis Output Control settings to Program Controlled/For Future Analysis and re-solve the modal analysis.

Configures the active load steps for the selected Table-defined Loads.

This is the "Load Step Activation" view for Table-defined Loads. It is used to activate or deactivate the selected Loads at corresponding load steps.

The columns that are displayed will change depending on the selected Loads in the Tree/Outline view. At a minimum, the "Load Step" and "Active" columns will be shown. The "Load Step" cells specifies the load step for that row. When multiple Loads are selected, a "Boundary Condition" column be shown. The "Boundary Condition" cells contain the names of the Loads affected by that row. When Loads from different Analyses are selected, an "Analysis" column will be shown. The "Analysis" cells show the parent Analysis for the Loads specified in the "Boundary Condition" column.

The "Active" column cells contain a checkbox that is used to activate or deactivate the corresponding Load(s) at that time step. Each checkboxe has three possible states: "Activated", "Deactivated", and "Indeterminate". The visual appearance and meaning of these states is shown below. Note that the header for the "Active" column also includes a master checkbox. This master checkbox can be used to uniformly activate or deactivate all selected Loads at each load step.

Provides a composite quality metric that ranges between 0 and 1. This metric is based on the ratio of the volume to the sum of the square of the edge lengths for 2D quad/tri elements, or the square root of the cube of the sum of the square of the edge lengths for 3D elements. A value of 1 indicates a perfect cube or square while a value of 0 indicates that the element has a zero or negative volume.
A composite quality metric ranging from 0 to 1. A value of 1 indicates a perfect element. A value of 0 indicates that the element has a zero or negative volume.
Provides aspect ratio for triangles and quadrilaterals using only the corner nodes of the element.

It is bounded by negative infinity and positive infinity, but all negative-value elements are collected and arbitrarily assigned the value -100. It is used by the MAPDL solver and is the inverse of Jacobian Ratio (Corner Nodes). An element with a Jacobian ratio less than or equal to 0 should be avoided.
It is bounded by -1 (worst) and 1 (best). An element with a Jacobian ratio less than or equal to 0 should be avoided.
It is bounded by -1 (worst) and 1 (best) but the calculation is less restrictive. An element with a Jacobian ratio less than or equal to 0 should be avoided.

It is computed and tested for some quadrilateral shell elements, and the quadrilateral faces of bricks, wedges, and pyramids. A high factor may indicate a condition the underlying element formulation cannot handle well, or may simply hint at a mesh generation flaw.
Provides the parallel deviation for quadrilaterals.
It is computed and tested for all except Emag elements. Some in the finite element community have reported that large angles (approaching 180°) degrade element performance, while small angles don't.
Skewness determines how close to ideal (equilateral or equiangular) a face or cell is.
It is bounded by the values 0 (worst) and 1 (best).
It is used to compute the time step that satisfies the Courant-Friedrichs-Lewy (CFL) condition for a given analysis setup.

The smallest angle between the two edge elements of the triangular element.
It is used to compute the time step that satisfies the Courant-Friedrichs-Lewy (CFL) condition for a given analysis setup. This is the LS-Dyna formulation.
The largest angle between the two edge elements of the triangular element.
The smallest angle between the two edge elements of the quadrilateral mesh.
The largest angle between the two edge elements of the quadrilateral mesh.
Warping Angle is the angular measure of deviation of the element plane. The quad is divided into two triangles along the diagonal and the angle between the normals of the triangles are measured.

Tet collapse is a measure of tetrahedron “flatness”. It is defined as the min{h/[1.24*sqrt(A)]}, where h is the height of a corner node to opposite tetrahedron face and A is the area of the tetrahedron face. The range of allowed values for Tet Collapse is 0 (worst) to 1 (best).

Aspect Ratio (Height) is the ratio of the longest edge of an element to its shortest edge or the shortest distance from a corner node to the opposite edge (minimum normalized height). This is based upon the LS-Dyna formulation.
Minimum Element Edge Length is the shortest edge length of an element. For quadratic mesh, the length is the total of two segments from the start node to mid node and the end node to mid node.
Maximum Element Edge Length is the longest edge length of an element. For quadratic mesh, the length is the total of two segments from the start node to mid node and the end node to mid node.

The Forced Response Tool provides a comprehensive way of investigating the aeromechanics, and ultimately, the reliability of turbomachinery blade rows. Working in conjunction with Ansys CFD tools, the Force Response Tool accurately predicts the structural vibrations of industrial components. Advanced physical phenomena such as airfoil aeroelasticity, flutter, deterministic and probabilistic mistuning, as well as an array of loading and boundary conditions can be modeled and studied. Efficient high-fidelity modeling is achieved using a combination of core technologies such as cyclic symmetry and mode-superposition as well as innovative techniques to model mistuning and aeroelasticity in a reduced space. Based in Workbench Mechanical, the Forced Response Tool is the most intuitive, reliable, and efficient way to simulate turbomachinery blade rows.

The Bolt Tools Add-on provides helpers and quick actions to automate the standard modeling needs, like creating contacts and preloads. Use the Instance Manager for auto-recognition of geometry and grouping and to link to user-defined modeling routines in Mechanical. User Defined APDL modeling routines are linked to Mechanical coordinate systems.

Offshore exposes the OCEAN commands in Mechanical APDL, which can be used to include the hydrodynamic loads on submerged beam and pipe elements – resulting from the motion of the structure through the fluid, or from the fluid motion around the structure due to current or waves – in Static Structural, Transient Structural, Modal and Harmonic Response analyses.

Variable Load greatly simplifies the definition of complex loading for Rigid Dynamics systems. It allows you to create loads that depend on the state of the model, and to make these loads conditionally applied.
Motion Load Transfer allows you to apply the loads created in a Rigid Dynamics analysis on the flexible bodies in a Static Structural analysis.
The Distortion Compensation Add-on compensates the scoped geometry so that after loading or processing, the geometry distorts into the original target geometry.

The LPBF Process Add-on simplifies the setup of a Laser Powder Bed Fusion process analysis. A wizard steps through part and support identification, meshing, materials, process parameters, boundary conditions, and cutoff options. Completion of the wizard leaves the simulation ready to solve.

The DED process Add-on simplifies the setup for a Directed Energy Deposition (DED) process analysis. The DED wizard will step through part and baseplate identification, meshing, welding path definition, material parameters, machine settings, build and cooldown conditions, and base removal setup. Upon completion of the wizard, you will need to generate element clusters and then solve the simulation.

The Sintering Process Add-on simplifies the setup for a sintering process for a binder-jet manufactured part. The Add-on will add new result objects and load objects that describe the sintering process and underlying state variables. The wizard will step through part and support identification, meshing, material parameters, boundary conditions and recommended solver settings. Completion of the wizard leaves the simulation ready to be solved.

Hydrodynamic Pressure allows you to transfer external surface and internal tank pressures, selected loads and structural accelerations calculated in a Hydrodynamic Diffraction or time domain Hydrodynamic Response analysis onto panel and beam elements in a Static Structural analysis. This removes the need to create, manipulate and run hydrodynamic load files external to Workbench.

DesignLife Add-on is conceived to evaluate fatigue life. Using the results of finite element analysis (FEA) from Ansys Mechanical and Ansys LS-DYNA, it accumulates damage from repetitive loading to determine a product predicted life. You can quickly evaluate the effects of different materials and alternative geometries for new designs, and then optimize them for the product expected usage, long before the first prototype is built or expensive testing takes place.

The NVH Toolkit Add-on is conceived to postprocess Noise, Vibration and Harshness results. In addition, it streamlines FEA-Experimental model comparison calculations of Vibration results, like MAC, COMAC or FRFs. It also allows the identification of optimum sensor and exciter locations with Pre-Test.

The CP Microstructure Add-on is used to investigate, analyze, and leverage microstructural data derived from EBSD maps for the purpose of constructing a 3D, precision-representative model of a specified material.
The Add-ons Help button opens a browser with the Add-ons online documentation.

The Drop Test Add-on comprises a Wizard to automate the set up of a drop test analysis within an Explicit Dynamics or WB-LSDYNA analysis system from a geometry file of the object to be dropped. Once the Drop Test Add-on is loaded, you should be able to open the Drop Test Wizard. Activate either an Explicit Dynamics or LS-DYNA analysis and navigate to the Mechanical Environment Toolbar, then click the Drop Test Wizard icon to launch the wizard.

The Rotordynamics Add-on is created for users to fulfill acceptance criteria for Rotating Machinery design. It is compatible with both Beam and Solid Rotors. Engineers face the challenge of repetitively conducting rotodynamic analyses (preprocessing, analysis, and postprocessing) throughout the development process. Recognizing the need for a more efficient approach, the Rotordynamics Add-on centers around leveraging the capabilities of ANSYS Mechanical in this area.
